{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "As observed in Sect.",
    "\"AI biases, discrimination and unfairness\", most ML models are purely observational and rely on correlation among features.",
    "Consequently, they are not able to account for spurious effects.",
    "A principled way of tackling bias is to rely on causal reasoning (Nogueira et al., 2022; Spirtes & Zhang, 2016).",
    "The preferred causal framework used within ML is that of Perlian Causality, or Structural Causal Models (SCM) (Pearl, 2009)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "A principled way of tackling bias is to rely on causal reasoning (Nogueira et al., 2022; Spirtes & Zhang, 2016).",
    "The preferred causal framework used within ML is that of Perlian Causality, or Structural Causal Models (SCM) (Pearl, 2009)."
  ]
}